@chapter General Questions

@c --------------------
@section Where can I get the latest version of Dinotrace?

The latest version is Dinotrace @value{VERSION}.  It can be down-loaded
from the veripool, at
@uref{http://www.ultranet.com/~wsnyder/veripool/dinotrace}.

@c --------------------
@section Can I copy Dinotrace?

Dinotrace is covered under two Copyrights.  The latter one is the GNU
Copyleft, which allows free use and modification, provided that you in
turn provide free use and modification to all others that request it.
This is described in the @file{COPYING} distributed with Dinotrace.

Code created before 1998 was Copyrighted by Digital Equipment
Corporation.  Their Copyright also disclaims any warranties, and
disallows reproduction for sale.  Observing the GNU Copyleft should also
cover this Copyright for any software distributed not for a fee.  (The
water is murky if embeding Dinotrace.)

@c --------------------
@section Where should I report bugs and other problems with Dinotrace?

Currently the author is tracking bugs; contact
@email{wsnyder@@ultranet.com}.  There is a Anti-Spam filter on this
account, so be sure you have a valid return address to meet the filter's
challenge.

@c --------------------
@section What other public domain tools work with Dinotrace?

The primary tool you will want are GNU Emacs, with
@file{verilog-mode.el}, @file{dinotrace.el}, and @file{sim-log.el}
installed.  This will let you back annotate the values of signals onto
your source code.

You may also want Verilator, a public domain simulator, and other tools
available at the Veripool.

@c --------------------
@section Will Dinotrace work with Windows NT?

Yes, though it may not have the look and feel you expect.  (Where expect
is defined by Microsoft, not Unix.)  Some consider that a feature.

Read the installation instructions on the Website.  You'll need cygwin,
X11R6, and a X11 server, like Exceed or Excursion.

