@chapter On-line Help, Printed Manuals, Other Sources of Help

@c --------------------
@section How do I get a printed copy of the Dinotrace manual?

A PDF file is available at
@uref{http://www.ultranet.com/~wsnyder/veripool/dinotrace/dinotrace.pdf}.
Your web browser should be able to print this, if not you can probably
print the HTML version in the same directory.

The more ambitious can build the manual themselves.  The texinfo source
is included with Dinotrace.  Typing @samp{make dinotrace.dvi} will
create a dvi file that may then be printed with @samp{dvips}.  This will
require @prog{TeX}, @prog{texinfo}, and a bunch of libraries, all good
for a day's worth of downloading.

@c --------------------
@section How do I install a piece of Texinfo documentation?

A info file for Dinotrace comes with the package, @file{dinotrace.info}.
Copy this file to a directory in your info path, usually
@file{/usr/local/info}.  Then edit the master directory, usually
@file{/usr/local/info/dir} to include the line:
@example
  * Dinotrace: (dinotrace).  Signal waveform viewer
@end example

@c ======================================================================
@chapter Common Things People Want To Do 

@c --------------------
@section How do I have dinotrace always display a group of signals together?

Dinotrace doesn't really have the concept of groups yet.  Instead, use
the @config{signal_move} or @config{signal_copy} to accomplish the
desired effect.

For example, if out of a huge trace you want only @samp{foo} and @samp{bar}
to be displayed, put in your @file{dinotrace.dino}:

@example
signal_delete *
signal_add foo 
signal_add bar
@end example

Dinotrace will create similar code for you by selecting the
@dmenu{Customize Save As...} menu option then checking the @widget{Save
signal ordering} box.

@c --------------------
@section How do I make a signal that is a concatenation of other signals?

Dinotrace will only collapse signals with the same basename.  Make
another signal that is a concatenation of the two.

If the signal is never used, then it will be eliminated by Synopsys.  If
you're using Verilint or a similar tool that finds unused nets, you may
want to make another signal, unused_ok, to make it obvious that the net
is fake.  The below example does this.  It uses the weird ORing on
unused_ok so that any number of any width signals can be added in, yet
it will still always hold a constant high.

@example
wire [2:0] first;
wire [7:3] second;
wire [7:0] concatenated_for_dino = @{first, second@};
wire unused_ok = (|@{
                 concatenated_for_dino,
                 1'b1@});
@end example

@c --------------------
@section How do I find the next time a signal changes?

There is no direct way to move to the next edge.  You can see the next
time that the value changes by using @dmenu{Value Examine} or
@kbd{@key{MB2}}, then pan to that point manually or with @widget{Goto}.

@c --------------------
@section How do I make a "register window" with the values at a current time?

Just make a fake Verilog file with the registers laid out in ASCII as
you wish.  Then use the Emacs Dinotrace keys to annotate and manipulate
the values.  You can even have the signals commented out in your normal
module; annotation updates comments too.  (As long as the needed signals
are uncommented elsewhere in the module.)

