@chapter Bugs/Problems

@c --------------------
@section How do I get around the "Over maximum of 256 signal states" error message?

You have two basic options.  First, for one hot and similar state
machines, define another less wide signal that is derived from the wide
signal, then apply a @config{signal_state} command to that new signal.

Alternatively, do the decoding in Verilog.  A Configuration Command
@config{signal_radix *_ascii* ascii} with the code below should work:

@example
reg [8*4-1:0] machine_ascii;	// Decoded ascii state of machine
always @@ (/*AUTOSENSE*/machine) begin
   casex (@{machine@})
    4'b0000: machine_ascii = "----";
    4'b1000: machine_ascii = "s0  ";
    4'b0100: machine_ascii = "exit";
    4'b0010: machine_ascii = "stop";
    4'b0001: machine_ascii = "idle";
    default: machine_ascii = "%ERR";
   endcase
end
@end example

@c --------------------
@section Why do I see X's for a bus that isn't all X's?

If a signal value has even a single bit that is X or Z, but isn't
entirely X or Z, then it will be displayed as a X.  You can see the real
value by using @dmenu{Value Examine} or @kbd{@key{MB2}}.

@c --------------------
@section Why does(n't) Dinotrace compress bits into a single vector?

Dinotrace must form all vectors when the trace is being read in.  The
@config{vector_separator} command must be set to the character used to
separate bus bits from the rest of the signal name.  If you don't want
bits to be collapsed to vectors, just set it to some character that
doesn't occur in signal names, like @kbd{@@}.

@c --------------------
@section Why doesn't a signal appear in Dinotrace?

Check first that it is really in the trace.  The @prog{strings} program
will find signal names in every format that Dinotrace supports.

If the signal exists in the trace, it may have been deleted by a configuration
command.  Use the @dmenu{Signal Select} popup to add all signals, then
use @dmenu{Signal Search} to find it.

In Verilog DMP files, if a identical signal exists at many levels of
hierarchy, only the top level signal will exist.  If your naming
convention is sane, and doesn't change names at hierarchy boundaries,
you still should find the signal, just with a different hierarchy in
front of the base signal name.  Furthermore, signals with over 1024 bits
are dropped, since they would take too much space on the screen.

A bug is not impossible either, though usually Dinotrace manages to eek
out a warning message when it is about to loose a signal.

@c --------------------
@section Why doesn't a signal I can see in Dinotrace appear in the annotation?

Under the @dmenu{Value Annotate} is a option menu which chooses which
signals are included in the annotation.  By default, deleted signals
aren't included.  Often signals that are constant through the whole
trace are deleted, and thus don't get included in the annotation.
Change the option to include deleted signals, or add the needed signals
back.

@c --------------------
@section Why do I get the wrong value for a annotated signal?

Because you know more then Emacs.  (At least for the time being.)  Emacs
simply does a search and replace for the signal name, totally ignoring
the bus bits, module name, and hierarchy.

First off, this means bus subscripts are ignored.  The traced signal
@samp{foo[5:0]=6'b101010} when annotating @samp{foo[5]} will show the
value of the whole vector, not just bit 5: @samp{foo`101010'[5]}.

Furthermore, having multiple signals with the same name will confuse
things, as the hierarchy isn't known.  If the trace has the signals
@samp{a.foo[5:2]} and @samp{b.foo[5:2]} with different values, and the
code references foo, you could get either the a or b version.  Your best
bet is to delete the signals that don't apply to the module you are
annotating.  (If a signal like the clock is in many modules, but identical,
there's nothing to worry about.)

